<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
    Local-dev entitlements for ad-hoc-signed builds produced by
    Scripts/build-app.sh without SIGNING_IDENTITY set. macOS 26
    (Tahoe) tightened sandbox-profile compilation: a sandboxed app
    whose entitlements include team-bound capabilities
    (com.apple.developer.icloud-container-identifiers,
    com.apple.security.application-groups) but whose signature lacks
    a matching provisioning profile fails to launch with
    "Launchd job spawn failed" (NSPOSIXErrorDomain Code=163).

    Production DMG builds still use App/Reolens.entitlements, which
    has the full sandbox + iCloud + group entitlements. Those work
    because the release pipeline embeds a Developer ID provisioning
    profile alongside the signature, which AMFI validates against.

    Trade-offs for local dev with these slim entitlements:
      - No app sandbox: the dev binary has the same filesystem
        access as any user-owned process. Fine for testing.
      - No iCloud Drive sync: cameras.json reads/writes to the
        local Application Support fallback path, not the ubiquity
        container. Each dev build sees only its own camera list.
      - Network client + microphone access just work (those
        capabilities don't need entitlements outside the sandbox).
      - Library validation is disabled so Sparkle.framework
        (signed by the Sparkle Project, not us) loads correctly
        under hardened runtime.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
